AWS EC2 Deployment Guide

This project is a Flask app with local frontend assets and SQLite-style local state.
Use this guide when deploying it to an AWS EC2 instance.

Recommended stack
- Ubuntu 22.04 LTS on EC2
- Nginx as the public reverse proxy
- Gunicorn as the Python app server
- Systemd service for process management

High-level steps
1. Launch an EC2 instance.
2. Open inbound ports:
   - 22 for SSH
   - 80 for HTTP
   - 443 for HTTPS if you add TLS
3. Install system packages:
   - Python 3
   - pip
   - venv
   - nginx
   - git
4. Clone the repository onto the instance.
5. Create and activate a virtual environment.
6. Install Python dependencies from `requirements.txt`.
7. Set required environment variables for the app.
8. Run the Flask app behind Gunicorn.
9. Configure Nginx to proxy traffic to Gunicorn.
10. Create a systemd service so the app starts on reboot.

Example deployment pattern
- App working directory: `/opt/patient-intake`
- Gunicorn bind: `127.0.0.1:8000`
- Nginx public entrypoint: `http://your-domain-or-ec2-ip`

Suggested commands
```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y python3 python3-venv python3-pip nginx git
cd /opt
sudo git clone <your-repo-url> patient-intake
cd /opt/patient-intake
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Gunicorn example
```bash
gunicorn -b 127.0.0.1:8000 api.main:app
```

Systemd example
```ini
[Unit]
Description=Patient Intake App
After=network.target

[Service]
User=ubuntu
WorkingDirectory=/opt/patient-intake
Environment="FLASK_ENV=production"
ExecStart=/opt/patient-intake/.venv/bin/gunicorn -b 127.0.0.1:8000 api.main:app
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Nginx example
```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name _;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

Notes
- If the app writes uploads or local data, make sure the instance storage is persistent enough for your use case.
- If you want HTTPS, put the app behind a domain and add Certbot or an AWS load balancer.
- If you use any external APIs, confirm the required environment variables are set on the EC2 instance.

Operational checklist
- Verify the app starts on boot.
- Confirm uploads work.
- Confirm the submissions page loads.
- Confirm notifications still arrive.
- Test one full patient flow from intake to final code display.
